<p>&#8220;My experiences have led me to believe that one of the best things that men in a professional field can do for feminism is to learn to take sexual and romantic rejection well.&#8221;<span id="more-54449"></span></p>
<p>That&#8217;s one of the observations of a philosopher, going by the pseudonym &#8220;Alex Rails&#8221;, in the following guest post on issues at the intersection of sexual and professional ethics.</p>
<p>That description may lead one to think this post is about sexual harassment, and in a way it is, but it is mainly a virtue-based approach to the ethics of sexual relationships and flings between people in the profession, or, in the author&#8217;s terms, what it means to be a strong or weak &#8220;player&#8221;.</p>
<p>Unlike most of the other posts in the summer series, I did not solicit this one. It came to me from a pseudonymous author, and, reading an early draft, I was initially uncertain about proceeding with it, for surely there are some readers who will think that Rails is talking about how to do something bad well. But I think that if that&#8217;s your view, then you might frame what follows as a kind of non-ideal virtue theory. Alternatively, you might think, for a few reasons, that the optimal amount of sexual flings among people in the profession is, as Rails says, &#8220;not zero,&#8221; and that the question of how to engage in this behavior, given its moral riskiness, is worthwhile.</p>
<p>I do not know Rails&#8217; identity, but a third party I&#8217;m acquainted with who does confirmed that Rails is a tenured philosopher at a good university, writing sincerely and honestly. (If you want to reach out to Rails personally, you can do so by email to <a href="mailto:alexrails313@proton.me" target="_blank" rel="noopener">alexrails313@proton.me</a>.)</p>
<p>Discussion is welcome, but I ask that, given the subject matter, people exercise a bit of care with their comments. The comments section is <em>not </em>the place to name &#8220;players,&#8221; be they strong or weak, otherwise discuss the sex lives of identifiable individuals. If you wish to comment using a pseudonym but you&#8217;ve commented here previously under your real name, be sure to enter <em>both a new name and a new email address</em> when you comment, so your identity is not inadvertently revealed.</p>
<p>This is the ninth post in the <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/tag/summer-guest-post-series-2025/">2025 Summer Guest Post Series</a>. (As with the others, it will stay pinned to the top of the home page for a few days.)</p>
